sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKE THE LEAD AFTER WINNING THE INNINGS.
West Indies' Phil Simmons scored four runs for 38 on Friday as Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take the lead in the county championship.
However, their stay at the top may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in a rain-affected game against Nottinghamshire.
After scoring 83 in the first morning at Grace Road in Somerset, Leicestershire extended their first innings lead to 94 points, before scoring 296, with England's Andy Caddick scoring three for 83.
Somerset, who were 213 runs down, started their second innings steadily before Simmons stepped in to take them 174.
Essex, however, look set to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a firm grip in their game against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, who is regarded as England's one-day player of the year, scored 158, his first century of the season, as Essex reached 372 and took an 82-point lead into the first innings.

By the close Yorkshire had turned that into a 37-run advantage, but off-spinner Such had thwarted their hopes by taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on 119 for five and praying for rain.

At The Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man discarded by England, continued to silence his critics as he followed up his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out in Friday's game against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by England hope Mark Butcher, who scored 70 points as Surrey finished the game with a 429-point, seven-point lead, 234 points.
Derbyshire continued the hunt for their first title since 1936, reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in the second innings and still 100 runs short of avoiding defeat.
Australian Tom Moody scored six for 82, while Chris Adams (123) and Tim O'Gorman (109) gave Derbyshire a 471-point and 233-run lead in the first innings.
After the frustration caused by the weather, which had a very negative effect on the opening day, the Kent club improved their game to see off Nottinghamshire by 214 points.
They were held to 84 points by Paul Johnson, while former England fast-baller Martin McCague scored four for 55 points.
By stampede, Kent had reached 108 points on three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER IS APPOINTED ENGLAND CAPTAIN.
The world's most expensive footballer, Alan Shearer, was appointed England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who joined Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), replaces Tony Adams, who captained the team at the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are injured and will miss England's opening World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer is on trial as captain, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton captain should not take the job himself.
"I'm sure there will be no problems, I'm sure Alan is the right man for the job," said Hoddle.
"There were three or four people who could do it, but when I spoke to Alan, he was ready and very willing.
"It's very difficult to come to a 100% conclusion about something like this in four days...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows what the team situation is, even though he plays up front. "
On Friday, Shearer's Euro 96 forward Teddy Sheringham left the squad with an injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS BLOCKED AFTER VIOLENCE IN VOLGOGRAD.
"Rotor Volgograd must play their next home game behind closed doors after a 1-0 thrashing of Dynamo Moscow on Saturday ended Rotor's short-lived league lead.
Anatoly Gorokhovsky, head of the Russian league's Disciplinary Committee, announced on Friday that Rotor will play Lada Togliatti on 3 September in empty stands.
The club that knocked Manchester United out of the UEFA Cup last year is fined $1,000.
Despite the loss, Rotor is in a good position with 11 games left in the championship.
Volgograd is three points behind Alania and two behind Dinamo Moscow, but the leaders are a game ahead and Moscow is two behind.
BOXING - ROBERTO DURAN OF PANAMA FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran steps into the ring on Saturday for another shot at his long career.
The 45-year-old Duran will face the little-known 30-year-old Mexican Ariel Cruz in Panama in the super-heavyweight category without a title.
The fight, which will be Duran's first in his home country for 10 years, is called here "The Return of a Legend", and Duran still talks as if he is in his prime.
This match is to prepare me.
I'm not giving up my career," Duran told Reuters.
But people close to the boxer say that the man who has been champion in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses on Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's greatest boxers," said Ramon Manzanares, President of the Panama Boxing Association.
Duran, whose 97-12 record spans three decades, hopes a win in the 10-rounder will give him a rematch with Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho made a controversial points decision against Panamanian in the title fight in Atlantic City in June.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN DOUBLES UNDER LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi avoided disaster on Thursday, while Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcel Rios were less fortunate on a night of bad luck at the US Open.

Washington's number 11 was unable to repeat his Wimbledon miracle comeback, losing 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 to the hot-blooded wildcard Alex O'Brien in a two-hour and 51-minute battle on the Stadium Court.
In the stands, number 10 Rios lost to another Wimbledon-related player, bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The temperamental left-hander defeated the Chilean 6-4 4-6 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme was uneventful, although sixth-ranked former champion Agassi had to climb out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 hole, winning 18 of his last 19 games against India's Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who came back from 1-5 down in the third set of his Wimbledon semi-final against Todd Martin to drop two sets, looked ready for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first pro title in New Haven two weeks ago, served for the match in the third set at 5-4, but Washington fought back.
"I just keep telling myself: 'Keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, ranked 65th in the rankings.
"I kept my composure and I was proud of myself for that - normally I would have packed up my tent and gone home."
O'Brien, a former US student national champion and hard server, hit 17 aces to eventually defeat a never trailing Washington team.
The fifth set continued on serve until the sixth game when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand down the line, made it 4-2 with a backhand down the line. O'Brien took a 4-2 lead.
The Texan hit two aces to hold his serve (5:2) and then hit the eighth match ball when Washington found the net from 40:0 with another backhand ball.
"You just keep fighting and try to make him play a little bit.
I think he was a little tense at some points," Washington said. "
But I think he served quite well when it was needed. "

Tarango, who was fined $28,000 and banned from this year's All-England Club for a tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago, argued over calls and taunted fans during a two-hour-and-24-minute live tango with Rios in the stands.
The vigorous cheering section supported the scattered Chilean and embraced the American, who got all the attention.
"I'm an emotional player," said Tarango, ranked 104th. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match was decided in the third set, which the American won 7-5, much to the dismay of the crowd.
"I love the public if they call me names every day.
It cheers me up, makes me play my best tennis," said Tarango.
"I played my best tennis in college when fraternities poured beer on me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think it would be a lot more fun for everyone. "
For Rios Tarango, the jumps were not encouraging.
"He always complains too much," said Rios. "
But I don't think it is.
I think I played very badly.
It was hard to play at night.
I lost too many points that I never lost.
"I don't see the ball as I see it during the day.
I play American, so I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango sarcastically kissed the crowd, then jigged his body for the Rios fan section to give him a shouted salute.
"I share their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the supporters. "
At the same time, they shout against me.
After I won, I thought I could give them a little shine. "
NFL AMERICAN FOOTBALL - RANDALL CUNNINGHAM RETIRES.
Randall Cunningham, the National Football League's all-time leading scorer as a defensive forward and one of the most athletic players ever to play the centre position, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham spent his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
Cunningham is a three-time Pro Bowl selection who gained 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I would like to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful fans in Philadelphia for their support throughout my career," said Cunningham.
"Although I am sad to leave, I am looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for some time."
"Randall was one of the most exciting offensive linemen in NFL history," said Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was a cornerstone of the Eagles franchise and provided many great moments for fans in Philadelphia and across the NFL. "
In 1985, Cunningham was selected in the second round and completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7%) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already signed a contract with the broadcaster.
